{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583103"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:07:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:07:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2000"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2000"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.12,0.26,0.47,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82712"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2000"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67847"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5394"},{"type":"tags","id":"9585"},{"type":"tags","id":"12798"},{"type":"tags","id":"12803"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"775"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82712"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA randomised controlled trial is conducted to evaluate a new drug for preventing myocardial infarction. In the treatment group, one of 100 patients experienced a myocardial infarction during the study period. In the control group receiving placebo, two of 100 patients experienced a myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the number needed to treat to prevent one myocardial infarction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1","10","50","100","200"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELet\u0027s first construct a 2x2 table to organise the data:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00271\u0027 style=\u0027border-collapse: collapse; margin: 10px 0;\u0027\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EMI\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ENo MI\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ETotal\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETreatment\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E99\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E100\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EControl\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E2\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E98\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E100\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo calculate the number needed to treat (NNT), we first need to determine the absolute risk reduction (ARR). The control event rate is 2/100 = 0.02 or 2%. The treatment event rate is 1/100 = 0.01 or 1%. Therefore, the ARR = 0.02 - 0.01 = 0.01 or 1%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E100\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because NNT = 1/ARR = 1/0.01 = 100. This means we need to treat 100 patients with the new drug to prevent one myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn NNT of \u003Cstrong\u003E1\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate that every single patient treated benefits from the intervention, which is unrealistic for most medical treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E10\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest a much larger treatment effect than what was observed in this trial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E50\u003C/strong\u003E would result from an ARR of 0.02 or 2%, which is not correct based on the data provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E200\u003C/strong\u003E would result from an ARR of 0.005 or 0.5%, which is smaller than the actual ARR in this study.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe NNT is a clinically useful measure as it provides an intuitive way to understand the magnitude of a treatment effect. A larger NNT indicates that more patients need to be treated to prevent one adverse outcome, suggesting a smaller treatment effect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Number needed to treat (NNT) is calculated as 1 divided by the absolute risk reduction (ARR)","Absolute risk reduction (ARR) is calculated by subtracting the event rate in the treatment group from the event rate in the control group","A larger NNT indicates a smaller treatment effect"],"references":["Ochsner J, 2006. \u2018Clinicians\u2019 Guide to Statistics for Medical Practice and Research: Part I\u2019 in The Ochsner Journal, vol. 6, pp 68-83."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67847"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2000"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67847"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T20:42:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T20:43:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2000"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82712"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"posit